Not exactly. Recent prices get higher weight than older prices. As a simple example you can have an EMA with todays price times 1/2, yesterdays times 1/4, the day before times 1/8, then 1/16, and so on. Total weight of the infinite sum is 1. Because these weights form an exponential `1/2^n` it is called *exponential* moving average. You can use a different exponential (as in dtao, a slow one) but a recent price point will always carry more weight than an older price point. What Maciej tries to convey is that the totality of “days before yesterday” carries more weight than the price of yesterday. So one datapoint should not have a large impact on the EMA (which is only true when looking at impact on absolute value, but that’s a different topic)

Ps. And why do people use EMAs? Because it is computationally cheap. You just need the last EMA value and the newest point. Consider calculating “the average of last month” and suddenly you need to keep track of 31 datapoints, because every day you add todays price and subtract a one month old price from the moving average.
You can think of many other ways to calculate a moving average, but EMA often has quite a good cost-benefit ratio. (But that’s mostly due to the extremely low cost IMO)

```python

import bittensor as bt
sub = bt.subtensor('finney')
subnets = sub.all_subnets()

tao_weight = 0.18
total_tao_out = 0
root_tao = float(subnets[0].tao_in)
pools = [ Subnet( float(si.tao_in), float(si.alpha_in), float(si.alpha_out)) for si in subnets if si.netuid != 0 ]
for i, p in enumerate( pools ):
    tao_in = float(subnets[i + 1].tao_in_emission)
    alpha_in = float(subnets[ i + 1].alpha_in_emission)
    alpha_out = float( subnets[i + 1].alpha_out_emission)
    p.inject( tao_in, alpha_in, alpha_out )
    
    prop = (tao_weight * root_tao)/( (tao_weight * root_tao) + p.alpha_outstanding + p.alpha_reserve )
    total_tao_out += p.unstake( prop * alpha_out * 0.41 )
    

print( 'Required total TAO per block', total_tao_out)
```
